ElastiCache: Redis versus Memcached.

ElastiCache runs two engines, and choosing the wrong one is one of the more common architecture mistakes. Redis, and the newer Valkey fork, offers rich data structures: strings, hashes, lists, sets, sorted sets, bitmaps, HyperLogLog, streams, and geo. It has persistence, via R-D-B snapshots and A-O-F logs; replication, with Multi-A-Z automatic failover; cluster-mode sharding, up to five hundred shards; plus pub/sub, Lua scripting, transactions, and backup and restore. It's mostly single-threaded. Memcached is deliberately simpler: strings only, with no persistence, no replication, and no failover, but it's multi-threaded, so it scales with C-P-U cores, and it scales horizontally by adding nodes, using client-side consistent hashing and Auto Discovery. The default is Redis; pick Memcached only for genuinely simple key-value caching where multi-thread throughput matters and losing a node, which is rebuilt on the next miss, is acceptable.

Redis deploys as a replication group: one primary plus up to five replicas, with Multi-A-Z promoting a replica on failure. Cluster Mode Disabled is one shard, up to about five hundred gigabytes on a single primary; Cluster Mode Enabled shards the keyspace across up to five hundred shards for linear write scaling, and the client connects to the configuration endpoint.

Zooming out, the tier stacks; it doesn't replace. The source of truth is always relational, on R-D-S or Aurora. Availability is Multi-A-Z, Aurora replicas, or Global Database. Connection pooling is R-D-S Proxy whenever Lambda is involved. Read scaling is read replicas first, then ElastiCache in front of the heavy repeated reads. And anything needing sub-millisecond latency, like session lookups, rate-limit counters, or hot leaderboards, belongs in ElastiCache, not the database. Durable state lives in the database; the hot subset lives in the cache.
